-- Foreign Investors Buy Net 4.15 Billion Rupees of Indian Stocks
-- B y   P a r e s h   J a t a k i a
-- 2012-08-30T10:26:01Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-08-30/foreign-investors-buy-net-4-15-billion-rupees-of-indian-stocks.html
Overseas  funds  bought a net  4.15
billion rupees  ($74.5 million) of Indian equities yesterday, the
22nd day of purchases, according to the market regulator.  Foreigners bought 22.4 billion rupees of shares and sold
18.3 billion rupees, the Securities & Exchange Board of India
said on its  website  today. They have invested a total $11.85
billion in local equities this year.  The benchmark  BSE India Sensitive Index (SENSEX)  has increased 13
percent this year, helped by the biggest overseas equity flows
among 10 Asian markets tracked by Bloomberg. Flows surged to a
record in 2010, making the Sensex the best performer among the
worldâ€™s top 10 markets. The largest-ever outflow in 2008 led the
biggest annual slump of 52 percent.  Offshore funds sold a net 14.4 billion rupees of bonds
yesterday, reducing their inflow into debt this year to 241
billion rupees, the data  show .  Foreigners have invested 5.05 trillion rupees in stocks and
1.448 trillion rupees in bonds since they were allowed into the
country in 1993.  The regulator provides data on shares bought and sold by
large investors, including trades in the primary and secondary
markets, with a delay of at least a day.  To contact the reporter on this story:
